><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Just to clarify </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">the issue of the referendum, since both of you have raised it, I take it that it is not necessarily the principle of having a referendum on the devolution of income tax powers </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">a concern; it is</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> rather the fact that the powers for income tax variation as it stands in the current draft Bill would be practically unusable even if there was a yes vote in the referendum. Is that your real </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">position</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Professor </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Wyn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> Jones</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">No, that is not my position, but I do not know about Roger</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">s. My own position is that I am against this on principle, and can I explain why?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight